[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] When you're writing tests, you often need to check that values meet certain conditions.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect` gives you access to a number of "matchers" that let you validate different things.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For additional Jest matchers maintained by the Jest Community check out `jest-extended`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Consult the Getting Started guide for details on how to setup Jest with TypeScript.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The `expect` function is used every time you want to test a value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You will rarely call `expect` by itself.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Instead, you will use `expect` along with a "matcher" function to assert something about a value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It's easier to understand this with an example.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Let's say you have a method `bestLaCroixFlavor()` which is supposed to return the string `'grapefruit'`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] In this case, `toBe` is the matcher function.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] There are a lot of different matcher functions, documented below, to help you test different things.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The argument to `expect` should be the value that your code produces, and any argument to the matcher should be the correct value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you mix them up, your tests will still work, but the error messages on failing tests will look strange.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you know how to test something, `.not` lets you test its opposite.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `resolves` to unwrap the value of a fulfilled promise so any other matcher can be chained.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If the promise is rejected the assertion fails.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Since you are still testing promises, the test is still asynchronous.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Hence, you will need to tell Jest to wait by returning the unwrapped assertion.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.rejects` to unwrap the reason of a rejected promise so any other matcher can be chained.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If the promise is fulfilled the assertion fails.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Alternatively, you can use `async/await` in combination with `.rejects`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBe` to compare primitive values or to check referential identity of object instances.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It calls `Object.is` to compare values, which is even better for testing than `===` strict equality operator.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Don't use `.toBe` with floating-point numbers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, due to rounding, in JavaScript `0.2 + 0.1` is not strictly equal to `0.3`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you have floating point numbers, try `.toBeCloseTo` instead.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Although the `.toBe` matcher **checks** referential identity, it **reports** a deep comparison of values if the assertion fails.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If differences between properties do not help you to understand why a test fails, especially if the report is large, then you might move the comparison into the `expect` function.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveBeenCalled` to ensure that a mock function was called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a `drinkAll(drink, flavour)` function that takes a `drink` function and applies it to all available beverages.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You might want to check that `drink` gets called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveBeenCalledTimes` to ensure that a mock function got called exact number of times.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a `drinkEach(drink, Array<flavor>)` function that takes a `drink` function and applies it to array of passed beverages.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You might want to check that drink function was called exact number of times.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveBeenCalledWith` to ensure that a mock function was called with specific arguments.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The arguments are checked with the same algorithm that `.toEqual` uses.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say that you can register a beverage with a `register` function, and `applyToAll(f)` should apply the function `f` to all registered beverages.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you have a mock function, you can use `.toHaveBeenLastCalledWith` to test what arguments it was last called with.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a `applyToAllFlavors(f)` function that applies `f` to a bunch of flavors, and you want to ensure that when you call it, the last flavor it operates on is `'mango'`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you have a mock function, you can use `.toHaveBeenNthCalledWith` to test what arguments it was nth called with.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a `drinkEach(drink, Array<flavor>)` function that applies `f` to a bunch of flavors, and you want to ensure that when you call it, the first flavor it operates on is `'lemon'` and the second one is `'octopus'`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The nth argument must be positive integer starting from 1.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you have a mock function, you can use `.toHaveReturned` to test that the mock function successfully returned (i.e., did not throw an error) at least one time.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a mock `drink` that returns `true`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveReturnedTimes` to ensure that a mock function returned successfully (i.e., did not throw an error) an exact number of times.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Any calls to the mock function that throw an error are not counted toward the number of times the function returned.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveReturnedWith` to ensure that a mock function returned a specific value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say you have a mock `drink` that returns the name of the beverage that was consumed.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveLastReturnedWith` to test the specific value that a mock function last returned.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If the last call to the mock function threw an error, then this matcher will fail no matter what value you provided as the expected return value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveNthReturnedWith` to test the specific value that a mock function returned for the nth call.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If the nth call to the mock function threw an error, then this matcher will fail no matter what value you provided as the expected return value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveLength` to check that an object has a `.length` property and it is set to a certain numeric value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This is especially useful for checking arrays or strings size.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toHaveProperty` to check if property at provided reference `keyPath` exists for an object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For checking deeply nested properties in an object you may use dot notation or an array containing the keyPath for deep references.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can provide an optional `value` argument to compare the received property value (recursively for all properties of object instances, also known as deep equality, like the `toEqual` matcher).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The following example contains a `houseForSale` object with nested properties.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] We are using `toHaveProperty` to check for the existence and values of various properties in the object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `toBeCloseTo` to compare floating point numbers for approximate equality.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The optional `numDigits` argument limits the number of digits to check **after** the decimal point.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For the default value `2`, the test criterion is `Math.abs(expected - received) < 0.005` (that is, `10 ** -2 / 2`).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Intuitive equality comparisons often fail, because arithmetic on decimal (base 10) values often have rounding errors in limited precision binary (base 2) representation.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Because floating point errors are the problem that `toBeCloseTo` solves, it does not support big integer values.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeDefined` to check that a variable is not undefined.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You could write `expect(fetchNewFlavorIdea()).not.toBe(undefined)`, but it's better practice to avoid referring to `undefined` directly in your code.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeFalsy` when you don't care what a value is and you want to ensure a value is false in a boolean context.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You may not care what `getErrors` returns, specifically - it might return `false`, `null`, or `0`, and your code would still work.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] In JavaScript, there are six falsy values: `false`, `0`, `''`, `null`, `undefined`, and `NaN`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `toBeGreaterThan` to compare `received > expected` for number or big integer values.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `toBeGreaterThanOrEqual` to compare `received >= expected` for number or big integer values.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `toBeLessThan` to compare `received < expected` for number or big integer values.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `toBeLessThanOrEqual` to compare `received <= expected` for number or big integer values.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeInstanceOf(Class)` to check that an object is an instance of a class.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This matcher uses `instanceof` underneath.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `.toBeNull()` is the same as `.toBe(null)` but the error messages are a bit nicer.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] So use `.toBeNull()` when you want to check that something is null.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeTruthy` when you don't care what a value is and you want to ensure a value is true in a boolean context.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You may not care what `thirstInfo` returns, specifically - it might return `true` or a complex object, and your code would still work.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeUndefined` to check that a variable is undefined.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You could write `expect(bestDrinkForFlavor('octopus')).toBe(undefined)`, but it's better practice to avoid referring to `undefined` directly in your code.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toBeNaN` when checking a value is `NaN`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toContain` when you want to check that an item is in an array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For testing the items in the array, this uses `===`, a strict equality check.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `.toContain` can also check whether a string is a substring of another string.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This matcher also accepts others iterables such as strings, sets, node lists and HTML collections.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toContainEqual` when you want to check that an item with a specific structure and values is contained in an array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For testing the items in the array, this matcher recursively checks the equality of all fields, rather than checking for object identity.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toEqual` to compare recursively all properties of object instances (also known as "deep" equality).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It calls `Object.is` to compare primitive values, which is even better for testing than `===` strict equality operator.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `toEqual` ignores object keys with `undefined` properties, `undefined` array items, array sparseness, or object type mismatch.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] To take these into account use `.toStrictEqual` instead.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `.toEqual` won't perform a *deep equality* check for two errors.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Only the `message` property of an Error is considered for equality.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is recommended to use the `.toThrow` matcher for testing against errors.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toMatch` to check that a string matches a regular expression.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, you might not know what exactly `essayOnTheBestFlavor()` returns, but you know it's a really long string, and the substring `grapefruit` should be in there somewhere.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toMatchObject` to check that a JavaScript object matches a subset of the properties of an object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It will match received objects with properties that are **not** in the expected object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can also pass an array of objects, in which case the method will return true only if each object in the received array matches (in the `toMatchObject` sense described above) the corresponding object in the expected array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This is useful if you want to check that two arrays match in their number of elements, as opposed to `arrayContaining`, which allows for extra elements in the received array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can match properties against values or against matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This ensures that a value matches the most recent snapshot.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Check out the Snapshot Testing guide for more information.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can provide an optional `propertyMatchers` object argument, which has asymmetric matchers as values of a subset of expected properties, **if** the received value will be an **object** instance.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is like `toMatchObject` with flexible criteria for a subset of properties, followed by a snapshot test as exact criteria for the rest of the properties.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can provide an optional `hint` string argument that is appended to the test name.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Although Jest always appends a number at the end of a snapshot name, short descriptive hints might be more useful than numbers to differentiate **multiple** snapshots in a **single** `it` or `test` block.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Jest sorts snapshots by name in the corresponding `.snap` file.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Ensures that a value matches the most recent snapshot.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Jest adds the `inlineSnapshot` string argument to the matcher in the test file (instead of an external `.snap` file) the first time that the test runs.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Check out the section on Inline Snapshots for more info.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toStrictEqual` to test that objects have the same structure and type.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toThrow` to test that a function throws when it is called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You must wrap the code in a function, otherwise the error will not be caught and the assertion will fail.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toThrowErrorMatchingSnapshot` to test that a function throws an error matching the most recent snapshot when it is called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Check out React Tree Snapshot Testing for more information on snapshot testing.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Use `.toThrowErrorMatchingInlineSnapshot` to test that a function throws an error matching the most recent snapshot when it is called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.anything()` matches anything but `null` or `undefined`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] You can use it inside `toEqual` or `toHaveBeenCalledWith` instead of a literal value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.any(constructor)` matches anything that was created with the given constructor or if it's a primitive that is of the passed type.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.arrayContaining(array)` matches a received array which contains all of the elements in the expected array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] That is, the expected array is a **subset** of the received array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Therefore, it matches a received array which contains elements that are **not** in the expected array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.not.arrayContaining(array)` matches a received array which does not contain all of the elements in the expected array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] That is, the expected array **is not a subset** of the received array.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is the inverse of `expect.arrayContaining`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.arrayOf(value)` matches a received array whose elements match the provided value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This is useful for asserting that every item in an array satisfies a particular condition or type.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.not.arrayOf(value)` matches a received array where not all elements match the provided matcher.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.closeTo(number, numDigits?)` is useful when comparing floating point numbers in object properties or array item.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] If you need to compare a number, please use `.toBeCloseTo` instead.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For the default value `2`, the test criterion is `Math.abs(expected - received) < 0.005 (that is, 10 ** -2 / 2)`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.objectContaining(object)` matches any received object that recursively matches the expected properties.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] That is, the expected object is a **subset** of the received object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Therefore, it matches a received object which contains properties that **are present** in the expected object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Instead of literal property values in the expected object, you can use matchers, `expect.anything()`, and so on.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say that we expect an `onPress` function to be called with an `Event` object, and all we need to verify is that the event has `event.x` and `event.y` properties.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.not.objectContaining(object)` matches any received object that does not recursively match the expected properties.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] That is, the expected object **is not a subset** of the received object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] Therefore, it matches a received object which contains properties that are **not** in the expected object.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is the inverse of `expect.objectContaining`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.stringContaining(string)` matches the received value if it is a string that contains the exact expected string.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.not.stringContaining(string)` matches the received value if it is not a string or if it is a string that does not contain the exact expected string.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is the inverse of `expect.stringContaining`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.stringMatching(string | regexp)` matches the received value if it is a string that matches the expected string or regular expression.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This example also shows how you can nest multiple asymmetric matchers, with `expect.stringMatching` inside the `expect.arrayContaining`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.not.stringMatching(string | regexp)` matches the received value if it is not a string or if it is a string that does not match the expected string or regular expression.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] It is the inverse of `expect.stringMatching`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.assertions(number)` verifies that a certain number of assertions are called during a test.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] This is often useful when testing asynchronous code, in order to make sure that assertions in a callback actually got called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say that we have a function `doAsync` that receives two callbacks `callback1` and `callback2`, it will asynchronously call both of them in an unknown order.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The `expect.assertions(2)` call ensures that both callbacks actually get called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `expect.hasAssertions()` verifies that at least one assertion is called during a test.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] For example, let's say that we have a few functions that all deal with state.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] `prepareState` calls a callback with a state object, `validateState` runs on that state object, and `waitOnState` returns a promise that waits until all `prepareState` callbacks complete.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p01] The `expect.hasAssertions()` call ensures that the `prepareState` callback actually gets called.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You can use `expect.addEqualityTesters` to add your own methods to test if two objects are equal.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, let's say you have a class in your code that represents volume and can determine if two volumes using different units are equal.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You may want `toEqual` (and other equality matchers) to use this custom equality method when comparing to Volume classes.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Custom testers are functions that return either the result (`true` or `false`) of comparing the equality of the two given arguments or `undefined` if the tester does not handle the given objects and wants to delegate equality to other testers (for example, the builtin equality testers).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Custom testers are called with 3 arguments: the two objects to compare and the array of custom testers (used for recursive testers, see the section below).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This is a deep-equality function that will return `true` if two objects have the same values (recursively).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] It optionally takes a list of custom equality testers to apply to the deep equality checks.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If you use this function, pass through the custom testers your tester is given so further equality checks `equals` applies can also use custom testers the test author may have configured.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] See the example in the Recursive custom equality testers section for more details.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Matchers are methods available on `expect`, for example `expect().toEqual()`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] A tester is a method used by matchers that do equality checks to determine if objects are the same.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Custom matchers are good to use when you want to provide a custom assertion that test authors can use in their tests.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, the `toBeWithinRange` example in the `expect.extend` section is a good example of a custom matcher.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Sometimes a test author may want to assert two numbers are exactly equal and should use `toBe`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Other times, however, a test author may want to allow for some flexibility in their test, and `toBeWithinRange` may be a more appropriate assertion.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Custom equality testers are good for globally extending Jest matchers to apply custom equality logic for all equality comparisons.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Test authors can't turn on custom testers for certain assertions and turn them off for others (a custom matcher should be used instead if that behavior is desired).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, defining how to check if two `Volume` objects are equal for all matchers would be a good custom equality tester.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If your custom equality testers are testing objects with properties you'd like to do deep equality with, you should use the `this.equals` helper available to equality testers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This `equals` method is the same deep equals method Jest uses internally for all of its deep equality comparisons.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] It's the method that invokes your custom equality tester.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] It accepts an array of custom equality testers as a third argument.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Custom equality testers are also given an array of custom testers as their third argument.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Pass this argument into the third argument of `equals` so that any further equality checks deeper into your object can also take advantage of custom equality testers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, let's say you have a `Book` class that contains an array of `Author` classes and both of these classes have custom testers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Remember to define your equality testers as regular functions and **not** arrow functions in order to access the tester context helpers (e.g.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You can call `expect.addSnapshotSerializer` to add a module that formats application-specific data structures.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For an individual test file, an added module precedes any modules from `snapshotSerializers` configuration, which precede the default snapshot serializers for built-in JavaScript types and for React elements.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The last module added is the first module tested.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] See configuring Jest for more information.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You can use `expect.extend` to add your own matchers to Jest.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, let's say that you're testing a number utility library and you're frequently asserting that numbers appear within particular ranges of other numbers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The type declaration of the matcher can live in a `.d.ts` file or in an imported `.ts` module (see JS and TS examples above respectively).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If you keep the declaration in a `.d.ts` file, make sure that it is included in the program and that it is a valid module, i.e. it has at least an empty `export {}`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] `expect.extend` also supports async matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Async matchers return a Promise so you will need to await the returned value.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Let's use an example matcher to illustrate the usage of them.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] We are going to implement a matcher called `toBeDivisibleByExternalValue`, where the divisible number is going to be pulled from an external source.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Matchers should return an object (or a Promise of an object) with two keys.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] `pass` indicates whether there was a match or not, and `message` provides a function with no arguments that returns an error message in case of failure.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Thus, when `pass` is false, `message` should return the error message for when `expect(x).yourMatcher()` fails.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] And when `pass` is true, `message` should return the error message for when `expect(x).not.yourMatcher()` fails.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] A boolean to let you know this matcher was called with the negated `.not` modifier allowing you to display a clear and correct matcher hint (see example code).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] It optionally takes a list of custom equality testers to apply to the deep equality checks (see `this.customTesters` below).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] A boolean to let you know this matcher was called with an `expand` option.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] When Jest is called with the `--expand` flag, `this.expand` can be used to determine if Jest is expected to show full diffs and errors.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] There are a number of helpful tools exposed on `this.utils` primarily consisting of the exports from `jest-matcher-utils`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The most useful ones are `matcherHint`, `printExpected` and `printReceived` to format the error messages nicely.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] When an assertion fails, the error message should give as much signal as necessary to the user so they can resolve their issue quickly.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You should craft a precise failure message to make sure users of your custom assertions have a good developer experience.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If your matcher does a deep equality check using `this.equals`, you may want to pass user-provided custom testers to `this.equals`.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The custom equality testers the user has provided using the `addEqualityTesters` API are available on this property.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The built-in Jest matchers pass `this.customTesters` (along with other built-in testers) to `this.equals` to do deep equality, and your custom matchers may want to do the same.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] To use snapshot testing inside of your custom matcher you can import `jest-snapshot` and use it from within your matcher.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] It's also possible to create custom matchers for inline snapshots, the snapshots will be correctly added to the custom matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] However, inline snapshot will always try to append to the first argument or the second when the first argument is the property matcher, so it's not possible to accept custom arguments in the custom matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If your custom inline snapshot matcher is async i.e. uses `async`-`await` you might encounter an error like "Multiple inline snapshots for the same call are not supported".
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Jest needs additional context information to find where the custom inline snapshot matcher was used to update the snapshots properly.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Usually `jest` tries to match every snapshot that is expected in a test.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Sometimes it might not make sense to continue the test if a prior snapshot failed.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] For example, when you make snapshots of a state-machine after various transitions you can abort the test once one transition produced the wrong state.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] In that case you can implement a custom snapshot matcher that throws on the first mismatch instead of collecting every mismatch.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Returns the current state of the `expect` module.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This is useful for accessing test metadata inside `beforeEach`, `afterEach`, custom matchers, or any code that runs during a test.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The state object includes the following commonly used properties (among others).
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The full name of the currently running test, including all parent `describe` block names separated by a space.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] The absolute path to the test file being executed.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] A boolean indicating whether Jest was invoked with the `--expand` flag.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This is the same value available as `this.expand` inside custom matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Merges the provided object into the current matcher state.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This is primarily used internally and inside custom matchers.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Overwriting built-in state properties (such as `currentTestName`) may cause unexpected behavior.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] Serializable properties is a set of properties that are considered serializable by Jest.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This set is used to determine if a property should be serializable or not.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] If an object has a property that is not in this set, it is considered not serializable and will not be printed in error messages.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] You can add your own properties to this set to make sure that your objects are printed correctly.
[src:jest-testing/expect-p02] This will print only the `amount` and `unit` properties in the error message, ignoring the `label` property.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Let's get started by writing a test for a hypothetical function that adds two numbers.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Then, create a file named `sum.test.js`.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] This test used `expect` and `toBe` to test that two values were exactly identical.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] To learn about the other things that Jest can test, see Using Matchers.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] You can run Jest directly from the CLI (if it's globally available in your `PATH`, e.g. by `yarn global add jest` or `npm install jest --global`) with a variety of useful options.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] If you'd like to learn more about running `jest` through the command line, take a look at the Jest CLI Options page.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] The ideal configuration for Babel will depend on your project.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Jest will set `process.env.NODE_ENV` to `'test'` if it's not set to something else.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] You can use that in your configuration to conditionally setup only the compilation needed for Jest, e.g.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] `babel-jest` is automatically installed when installing Jest and will automatically transform files if a babel configuration exists in your project.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Most of the time you do not need to do anything special to work with different bundlers - the exception is if you have some plugin or configuration which generates files or have custom file resolution rules.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Jest can be used in projects that use webpack to manage assets, styles, and compilation. webpack does offer some unique challenges over other tools.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Refer to the webpack guide to get started.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Jest is not supported by Vite due to incompatibilities with the Vite plugin system.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] There are examples for Jest integration with Vite in the vite-jest library.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] However, this library is not compatible with versions of Vite later than 2.4.2.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] One alternative is Vitest which has an API that is compatible with Jest.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Jest can be used in projects that use parcel-bundler to manage assets, styles, and compilation similar to webpack.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Refer to the official docs to get started.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] First, make sure you followed the instructions on using Babel above.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Then add `@babel/preset-typescript` to the list of presets in your `babel.config.js`.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] However, there are some caveats to using TypeScript with Babel.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Because TypeScript support in Babel is purely transpilation, Jest will not type-check your tests as they are run.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] If you want that, you can use ts-jest instead, or just run the TypeScript compiler tsc separately (or as part of your build process).
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] ts-jest is a TypeScript preprocessor with source map support for Jest that lets you use Jest to test projects written in TypeScript.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] In order for Jest to transpile TypeScript with `ts-jest`, you may also need to create a configuration file.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] There are two ways to have Jest global APIs typed for test files written in TypeScript.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] You can use type definitions which ships with Jest and will update each time you update Jest.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] See the additional usage documentation of `describe.each`/`test.each` and `mock functions`.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Or you may choose to install the `@types/jest` package.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] It provides types for Jest globals without a need to import them.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] `@types/jest` is a third party library maintained at DefinitelyTyped, hence the latest Jest features or versions may not be covered yet.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Try to match versions of Jest and `@types/jest` as closely as possible.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] For example, if you are using Jest `27.4.0` then installing `27.4.x` of `@types/jest` is ideal.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] Jest can be used with ESLint without any further configuration as long as you import the Jest global helpers (`describe`, `it`, etc.) from `@jest/globals` before using them in your test file.
[src:jest-testing/getting-started] This is necessary to avoid `no-undef` errors from ESLint, which doesn't know about the Jest globals.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:jest-testing/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
